--- title: Makie subtitle: A data visualization ecosystem for Julia aliases: - makie_slides.html frontpic: "img/beautifulmakie.jpg" frontpicwidth: 40% author: Marie-HÃ©lÃ¨ne Burle date: 2022-10-26 date-format: long execute: freeze: auto cache: true error: true echo: true format: revealjs: embed-resources: true theme: [default, ../revealjs.scss] logo: /img/favicon_sfudrac.png highlight-style: monokai code-line-numbers: false template-partials: - ../title-slide.html pointer: color: "#b5111b" pointerSize: 32 link-external-newwindow: true footer:  Back to webinar page revealjs-plugins: - pointer --- # Introduction ## Plotting in Julia {.center} . . . Many options: - [Plots.jl](https://github.com/JuliaPlots/Plots.jl): high-level API for working with different back-ends (GR, Pyplot, Plotly...) - [PyPlot.jl](https://github.com/JuliaPy/PyPlot.jl): Julia interface to Matplotlib's `matplotlib.pyplot` - [PlotlyJS.jl](https://github.com/JuliaPlots/PlotlyJS.jl): Julia interface to plotly.js - [PlotlyLight.jl](https://github.com/JuliaComputing/PlotlyLight.jl): the fastest plotting option in Julia by far, but limited features - [Gadfly.jl](https://github.com/GiovineItalia/Gadfly.jl): following the grammar of graphics popularized by Hadley Wickham in R - [VegaLite.jl](https://github.com/queryverse/VegaLite.jl): grammar of interactive graphics - [PGFPlotsX.jl](https://github.com/KristofferC/PGFPlotsX.jl): Julia interface to the PGFPlots LaTeX package - [UnicodePlots.jl](https://github.com/JuliaPlots/UnicodePlots.jl): plots in the terminal ðŸ™‚ . . . - **[Makie.jl](https://github.com/MakieOrg/Makie.jl): powerful plotting ecosystem: animation, 3D, GPU optimization** ## Makie ecosystem {.center} . . . - Main package: + `Makie`: plots functionalities. Backend needed to render plots into images or vector graphics . . . - Backends: + `CairoMakie`: vector graphics or high-quality 2D plots. Creates, but does not display plots (you need an IDE that does or you can use [ElectronDisplay.jl](https://github.com/queryverse/ElectronDisplay.jl)) + `GLMakie`: based on [OpenGL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenGL); 3D rendering and interactivity in [GLFW](https://www.glfw.org/) window (no vector graphics) + `WGLMakie`: web version of `GLMakie` (plots rendered in a browser instead of a window) ## Extensions {.center} - [GeoMakie.jl](https://github.com/MakieOrg/GeoMakie.jl) add geographical plotting utilities to Makie - [AlgebraOfGraphics.jl](https://github.com/MakieOrg/AlgebraOfGraphics.jl/) turns plotting into a simple algebra of building blocks - [GraphMakie.jl](https://github.com/MakieOrg/GraphMakie.jl) to create network graphs ## Cheatsheet 2D {.center} ![From: [Storopoli, Huijzer and Alonso (2021). Julia Data Science. https://juliadatascience.io. ISBN: 97984898](https://juliadatascience.io/datavisMakie_attributes)](img/makiecheatsheet2D.png){width=55%} ## Cheatsheet 3D {.center} ![From: [Storopoli, Huijzer and Alonso (2021). Julia Data Science. https://juliadatascience.io. ISBN: 97984898](https://juliadatascience.io/datavisMakie_attributes)](img/makiecheatsheet3D.png){width="55%"} ## Resources {.center} - [Official documentation](https://docs.makie.org/stable/) - [Julia Data Science book, chapter 5](https://juliadatascience.io/DataVisualizationMakie) - Many examples in the project [Beautiful Makie](https://github.com/MakieOrg/BeautifulMakie) ## Troubleshooting {.center} Installing GLMakie can be challenging. [This page](https://github.com/MakieOrg/Makie.jl/tree/master/GLMakie#troubleshooting-opengl) may lead you towards solutions CairoMakie and WGLMakie should install without issues # Fundamental functioning ## Figure {.center} Load the package (here, we are using CairoMakie): ::: {#2 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using CairoMakie # no need to import Makie itself ``` ::: :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width="48%"} Create a `Figure` (container object): ::: {#4 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig = Figure() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="4%"} ::: ::: {.column width="48%"}
::: {#6 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(fig) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ``` Figure ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: --- You can customize a `Figure`: ::: {#8 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig2 = Figure(backgroundcolor=:grey22, size=(300, 300)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: Makie uses the [Colors.jl](https://github.com/JuliaGraphics/Colors.jl) package as a dependency \ You can find a list of all named colours [here](https://juliagraphics.github.io/Colors.jl/stable/namedcolors/) --- To use CSS specification (e.g. hex), you need to install Colors explicitly and use [its color parsing capabilities](http://juliagraphics.github.io/Colors.jl/stable/constructionandconversion/#Color-Parsing): ::: {#10 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using Colors fig3 = Figure(backgroundcolor=colorant"#adc2eb") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ## Axis {.center} :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width="48%"} Then, you can create an `Axis`: ::: {#12 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} ax = Axis(Figure()[1, 1]); ``` ::: ::: ::: {.column width="4%"} ::: ::: {.column width="48%"}
::: {#14 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(ax) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ``` Axis ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: --- ::: {#16 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Axis(fig3[1, 1]) # fig3[1, 1] sets the subplot layout: fig[row, col] fig3 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- ::: {#18 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Axis(fig[2, 3]) # This is what happens if we change the layout fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- ::: {#20 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Axis(fig3[2, 3]) # We can add another axis on fig3 fig3 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- Axis are customizable: ::: {#22 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig4 = Figure(size=(1000, 400)) Axis(fig4[1, 1], xlabel="x label", ylabel="y label", title="Plot title") fig4 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ## Add a plot {.center} ::: {#24 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code code-line-numbers="1-4|5|6"} fig = Figure(size=(1000, 400)) ax = Axis(fig[1, 1]) x = LinRange(-10, 10, 20) y = x scatter!(ax, x, y) # Functions with ! transform their arguments fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- Of course, there are many plotting functions, e.g. `scatterlines!`: ::: {#26 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig = Figure(size=(1000, 400)) ax = Axis(fig[1, 1]) x = LinRange(-10, 10, 20) y = x scatterlines!(ax, x, y) # Functions with ! transform their arguments fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- We can also use `lines!`: ::: {#28 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig = Figure(size=(1000, 400)) ax = Axis(fig[1, 1]) x = LinRange(-10, 10, 20) y = sin.(x) # The . means that the function is broadcast to each element of x lines!(ax, x, y) fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- Let's add points to get a smoother line: ::: {#30 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig = Figure(size=(1000, 400)) ax = Axis(fig[1, 1]) x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) y = sin.(x) # The . means that the function is broadcast to each element of x lines!(ax, x, y) fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- You don't have to create the `Figure`, `Axis`, and plot one at a time: ::: {#32 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) y = sin.(x) lines(x, y) # Note the use of lines instead of lines! ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- Or even more simply: ::: {#34 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) lines(x, sin) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- It is important to understand the concepts of `Figure` and `Axis` objects to customize them: ::: {#36 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) y = cos.(x) lines(x, y; figure=(; backgroundcolor=:green, size=(1000, 400)), axis=(; title="Cosinus function", xlabel="x label", ylabel="y label")) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ---

When you create the `Figure`, `Axis`, and plot at the same time, you create a `FigureAxisPlot` object: ::: {#38 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) y = cos.(x) obj = lines(x, y; figure=(; backgroundcolor=:green, size=(1000, 400)), axis=(; title="Cosinus function", xlabel="x label", ylabel="y label")); typeof(obj) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ``` Makie.FigureAxisPlot ``` ::: ::: :::{.note} Note the `;` in the `figure` and `axis` value. This is because these are one-element NamedTuples ::: --- The mutating functions (with `!`) can be used to add plots to an existing figure, but first, you need to decompose the `FigureAxisPlot` object: ::: {#40 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig, ax, plot = lines(x, sin) lines!(ax, x, cos) # Remember that we are transforming the Axis object fig # Now we can plot the transformed Figure ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: --- Or we can add several plots on different `Axis` in the same `Figure`: ::: {#42 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig, ax1, plot = lines(x, sin) ax2 = Axis(fig[1, 2]) lines!(ax2, x, cos) fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: # Examples ## 2D {.center} ::: {#44 .cell output-location='slide' execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using CairoMakie using StatsBase, LinearAlgebra using Interpolations, OnlineStats using Distributions CairoMakie.activate!(type="png") function eq_hist(matrix; nbins=256 * 256) h_eq = fit(Histogram, vec(matrix), nbins=nbins) h_eq = normalize(h_eq, mode=:density) cdf = cumsum(h_eq.weights) cdf = cdf / cdf[end] edg = h_eq.edges[1] interp_linear = LinearInterpolation(edg, [cdf..., cdf[end]]) out = reshape(interp_linear(vec(matrix)), size(matrix)) return out end function getcounts!(h, fn; n=100) for _ in 1:n vals = eigvals(fn()) x0 = real.(vals) y0 = imag.(vals) fit!(h, zip(x0,y0)) end end m(;a=10rand()-5, b=10rand()-5) = [0 0 0 a; -1 -1 1 0; b 0 0 0; -1 -1 -1 -1] h = HeatMap(range(-3.5,3.5, length=1200), range(-3.5,3.5, length=1200)) getcounts!(h, m; n=2_000_000) with_theme(theme_black()) do fig = Figure(figure_padding=0,size=(600,600)) ax = Axis(fig[1,1]; aspect=DataAspect()) heatmap!(ax,-3.5..3.5, -3.5..3.5, eq_hist(h.counts); colormap=:bone_1) hidedecorations!(ax) hidespines!(ax) fig end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ## 3D {.center} ```{.julia} using GLMakie, Random GLMakie.activate!() Random.seed!(13) x = -6:0.5:6 y = -6:0.5:6 z = 6exp.( -(x.^2 .+ y' .^ 2)./4) box = Rect3(Point3f(-0.5), Vec3f(1)) n = 100 g(x) = x^(1/10) alphas = [g(x) for x in range(0,1,length=n)] cmap_alpha = resample_cmap(:linear_worb_100_25_c53_n256, n, alpha=alphas) with_theme(theme_dark()) do fig, ax, = meshscatter(x, y, z; marker=box, markersize=0.5, color=vec(z), colormap=cmap_alpha, colorrange=(0,6), axis=(; type=Axis3, aspect=:data, azimuth=7.3, elevation=0.189, perspectiveness=0.5), figure=(; resolution=(1200,800))) meshscatter!(ax, x .+ 7, y, z./2; markersize=0.25, color=vec(z./2), colormap=cmap_alpha, colorrange=(0, 6), ambient=Vec3f(0.85, 0.85, 0.85), backlight=1.5f0) xlims!(-5.5,10) ylims!(-5.5,5.5) hidedecorations!(ax; grid=false) hidespines!(ax) fig end ``` ## 3D {.center} ![](img/makie_plot.jpg) # For more examples, have a look at [Beautiful Makie](https://github.com/MakieOrg/BeautifulMakie) ## Compiling sysimages {.center} While Makie is extremely powerful, its compilation time and its time to first plot are extremely long For this reason, it might save you a lot of time to create a sysimage (a file containing information from a Julia session such as loaded packages, global variables, compiled code, etc.) with [PackageCompiler.jl](https://github.com/JuliaLang/PackageCompiler.jl) :::{.note} The upcoming Julia 1.9 will do this automatically ::: # Using the Alliance clusters ## CairoMakie {.center} CairoMakie will run without problem on the Alliance clusters It is not designed for interactivity, so saving to file is what makes the most sense :::{.example} Example: ::: ```{.julia} save("graph.png", fig) ```
[Remember however that CairoMakie is 2D only (for now)]{.note} ## GLMakie {.center} GLMakie relies on [GLFW](https://www.glfw.org/) to create windows with OpenGL GLFW doesn't support creating contexts without an associated window The dependency [GLFW.jl](https://github.com/JuliaGL/GLFW.jl) will thus not install in the clustersâ€”even with X11 forwardingâ€”unless you use [VDI nodes](https://docs.alliancecan.ca/wiki/VNC#VDI_Nodes), [VNC](https://docs.alliancecan.ca/wiki/VNC), or [Virtual GL](https://virtualgl.org/) ## WGLMakie {.center} You can setup a server with [JSServe.jl](https://github.com/SimonDanisch/JSServe.jl) as per [the documentation](http://juliaplots.org/WGLMakie.jl/stable/) However, this method is intended for the creation of interactive widgets, e.g. for a website While this is really cool, it isn't optimized for performance There might also be a way to create an SSH tunnel to your local browser, although there is no documentation on this Best probably is to save to file ## Conclusion: Makie on production clusters {.center} - 2D plots: use CairoMakie and save to file - 3D plots: use WGLMakie and save to file
